main event: On 9 June 1953, in Tillamook, Oregon, two USAF officers reported a UFO sighting of a silvery, lens-shaped object estimated to be 25 feet in diameter. The object was observed for 8-10 seconds before disappearing in a north-westerly direction. No sound, trail, glow, or manner of propulsion was observed.
interesting points: The object was half-moon in shape and white in color, resembling the planet Venus.
The sighting lasted for 8-10 seconds and no manner of disappearance was reported.
A subsequent investigation concluded that the sighting was likely the planet Venus, as confirmed by Air Technical Intelligence Center's astronomers.

The report mentions another sighting on 29 June 1953, where an object with a half-moon shape and white colors was observed through a theodolite. No trail, exhaust, or known aerodynamic features were observed.
Questions were raised about the possibility of confusing weather conditions or the moon causing the sightings, indicating thorough consideration of alternative explanations.
result: prosaic explanation (Venus) in the first sighting, inconclusive for the second sighting
sighted object: silvery, lens-shaped object estimated to be 25 feet in diameter
